The WASP-126 Exoplanetary System


Overview

WASP-126 is a star with 1.12 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.27 times its radius. It is located NaN light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 6.4 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

WASP-126 is known to have undefined exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the WASP-126 system


WASP-126 b

WASP-126 b was discovered by the undefined observatory using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.04 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of WASP-126 b is 90.34697999999999 times the mass of Earth. The radius of WASP-126 b is 10.836 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, WASP-126 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.


WASP-126 c

WASP-126 c was discovered by the undefined observatory using the transit timing variations method. Its semi-major axis is NaN astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of WASP-126 c is 64.23282 times the mass of Earth. The radius of WASP-126 c is 9.38 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, WASP-126 c is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
